I think a lot about how the Millennials were the last generation able to build relationships with artists without being expected to view them critically.
We grew up in an golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to wonder where they came from, because that wasn't something you could easily figure out back then.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we placed them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
This was very different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches whenever they feel like it, posting "spoiler warnings" on social media or discussing them in closed groups.
Subconsciously, we long for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch shows like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," where there were so many one-liners that would now be memes.
We brought these jokes and assumed that most people would understand them.
Today, you can no longer take for granted that everyone knows something, even if it spreads virally.
There's too much, and there's no way to systematize it. Will we ever get out of this saturation?
We are trapped in a cycle, constantly discovering new content only to realize later that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
That's why we must hold onto our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works we liked can also have major flaws.
We approach parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We know that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes along the way.
Since our collective media consciousness has faded, we have developed a class consciousness that fosters critical thinking.
There are still those among us who raise someone to a pedestal only to be shocked when they fall down.
We are in a phase of transition, and I am curious to see where it will lead.
